Exception is an event during a program execution which disrupts the normal execution of the program.


Exception handling attempts to gracefully handle these situations so that a program (or worse, an entire system) does not crash.

In Java, when a code may throw an exception, it should be wrapped in a try block. Try block must be followed by one or more catch blocks. Catch blocks specify the type of exceptions as parameter. The catch block which matches the type of thrown object is executed whenever an exception is thrown. 
e.g.

try{
    file.read(m);
    System.out.println(m);
}
catch(IOException e){
    System.out.println("IO error");
}

Here the read() method may throw an IOException. If there is an exception, the execution jumps to catch block and execute the code in catch block, instead of crashing the program.

throw is used to throw an exception. But throws is used to specify what types of unhandled exceptions a function may throw. 

e.g.
   int readFile(String filename) throws IOException,MyException{
        if(filename==null)
             throw MyException;
   }


Throws specifier says that the function may throw IOException if there is an error in file operation.

In a function if the filename is null, then we are throwing an exception of the type MyException

