The synchronized keyword before a block means that any thread entering this block has to acquire the lock.  If the lok is already acquired by another thread, the former thread will enter the BLOCKED state and wait until the lock is released.

synchronized(object) {
    // ...
}

A synchronized  method has the same semantics, but the instance itself acts as a lock object.

synchronized void instanceMethod() {
    // ...
}

For a static synchronized method, the lock is the Class object representing the declaring class.

static synchronized void staticMethod() {
    // ...
}

Fail-Fast systems abort operation as-fast-as-possible exposing failures immediately and stopping the whole operation.

Whereas, Fail-Safe systems don't abort an operation in the case of a failure. Such systems try to avoid raising failures as much as possible.

Fail-fast iterators in Java don't play along when the underlying collection gets modified.

Collections maintain an internal counter called modCount. Each time an item is added or removed from the Collection, this counter gets incremented.

When iterating, on each next() call, the current value of modCount gets compared with the initial value. If there's a mismatch, it throws ConcurrentModificationException which aborts the entire operation.

Default iterators for Collections from java.util package such as ArrayList, HashMap, etc. are Fail-Fast.

e.g.
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.Iterator;
class ConcurrentExc{
     public static void main(String args[]){
   ArrayList<Integer> numbers = new ArrayList<Integer>();
   for(int i=0;i<10;i++)
      numbers.add(i*i);

Iterator<Integer> iterator = numbers.iterator();
while (iterator.hasNext()) {
    Integer number = iterator.next();
    numbers.add(50);
}
}
}

The statement numbers.add(50) throws ConcurrentModificationException because of failfast


Fail-Safe iterators favor lack of failures over the inconvenience of exception handling.

Those iterators create a clone of the actual Collection and iterate over it. If any modification happens after the iterator is created, the copy still remains untouched. Hence, these Iterators continue looping over the Collection even if it's modified.

However, it's important to remember that there's no such thing as a truly Fail-Safe iterator. The correct term is Weakly Consistent.

The Fail-Safe Iterators have a few disadvantages, though. One disadvantage is that the Iterator isn't guaranteed to return updated data from the Collection, as it's working on the clone instead of the actual Collection.

Another disadvantage is the overhead of creating a copy of the Collection, both regarding time and memory.

An interface which has only one abstract method is known as functional interface. It may have multiple static or abstract methods, but it can have exactly one abstract method. 

A functional interface is also called Single Abstract Method Interface SAM interface. 

Functional interface is a new feature in Java 8.

Such an interface can have an optional annotation- @FunctionalInterface . 

Lambda expressions can be used to represent the instance of a functional interface. 

e.g.
   @FunctionalInterface
   interface MathOp {
        public int add(int a, int b); 
  }

   class Demo{
         public static void main(String args[]){            
            int n1 =5;
            int n2 = 11;
            MathOp d1 = (a,b)->{return a+b;};
            System.out.println(d1.add(n1,n2));
        }
  }

Synax of lambda expression is 

   (argument-list) -> {body}

e.g.
   interface ABC{
        public String fun();
   }

   interface DEF {
        public int add(int a, int b); 
  }

   class Demo{
         public static void main(String args[]){
            ABC a1 =() ->{ return "Hello world";};//line 1
            System.out.println(a1.fun());
            int n1 =5;
            int n2 = 11;
            DEF d1 = (a,b)->{return a+b;};//line 2
            System.out.println(d1.add(n1,n2));
        }
  }

In the code, line 1 and line 2 are lambda expressions for anonymous classes which implement the interfaces ABC and DEF respectively.

line 1 takes no arguments and line 2 takes two arguments.

In the println() calls these lamda expressions are invoked.

An immutable class is a class, objects of which can not  be modified after they are created. 

String class of Java library is an immutable class , so are Integer, Float, Double and other wrapper classes.

To create our own immutable class, we have to make the class as final and its data members as final. The class must have a parameterized constructor, and must have getters for each of its data members and no setters methods.

